<p><b>Mithra</b> (<a href="/wiki/Avestan_language" title="Avestan language">Avestan</a> <i>Miθra</i>, modern <a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian</a> مهر <i>Mihr</i>, <i>Mehr</i>, <i>Meher</i>) is an important deity or divine concept (<a href="/wiki/Yazata" title="Yazata">Yazata</a>) in <a href="/wiki/Zoroastrianism" title="Zoroastrianism">Zoroastrianism</a> and later <a href="/wiki/Iranian_history" title="Iranian history" class="mw-redirect">Iranian history</a> and culture.</p>
<p>Mithra is descended, together with the <a href="/wiki/Historical_Vedic_religion" title="Historical Vedic religion">Vedic</a> deity <a href="/wiki/Mitra_(Vedic)" title="Mitra (Vedic)">Mitra</a>, from a common proto-Indo-Iranian entity *<i><a href="/wiki/Mitra" title="Mitra">mitra</a></i> "treaty, bond".</p>
